{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1782441380,"nonce":"E1h/pP87Dox2Xgmq1hmUqtExbJw=","message":"PostgreSQL upsert shipped in PR #52 (squash 5cb0e56).\n\nAPI: conn.to::\u003cT\u003e()...on_conflict(|t| target).do_nothing()|.do_update() then insert()/insert_returning(). do_update replaces every inserted column with EXCLUDED.col (insert-or-replace).\n\nDesign: do_nothing / replace-all do_update are param-free, so the conflict clause is a runtime Option\u003cConflictClause\u003e on the existing insert query object (no new query type, no param threading). Gated on a PostgreSQL-only OnConflictQueryBuilder (build_upsert returns the existing Self::Insert, reusing the whole execution path). Conflict target is a closure |t| col-or-tuple (ConflictTarget); EXCLUDED ref via a new Dialect::write_excluded_column seam; clause rendered in write_insert. A column-less (DEFAULT VALUES) do_update falls back to DO NOTHING. PG-localized: no other backend changed.\n\nTests: PG render (do_nothing / do_update / composite target / default-values fallback, all with RETURNING), a compile-fail proving the PG-only gate, and an #[ignore] integration round-trip. CI green; Codex clean.\n\nDeferred to follow-ups (see 8baec29): MySQL ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE; custom do_update(|excluded, current| ...) assignment closures; conflict-target PK/UNIQUE validation.\n\nClosing.","files":null}]}